text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: â€œwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.â€ documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takersâ€™ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebookâ€™s â€œplatform policyâ€ allowed only collection of friendsâ€™ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebookâ€™s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate â€œinformation warfareâ€ against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
i'm not making any resolutions for next year. i made a lot of changes this year, few of which were easy, all of which have made me feel like i'm living with more integrity. more integrity (and better skin). more integrity (and better hair). 1. fat is good for you. this is the year i gave up skimmed everything and went all-out full-fat. i rediscovered cheese. i put butter in everything. i ate more salt than i had done my entire life previously. i iearned, in short, to taste food again.

2.Â  go for the chop. "are you sure?" asked my hairdresser. "i've had a bad two years. this hair has seen some shit. take it all off please"

if you're in doubt, a haircut reminds you that you are never bound to being who you were, or thinking what you thought, or feeling what you felt.

3. fighting the patriarchy is easier in a team. full disclosure, it took me months to get on board with #metoo. i'm not proud. but this year i realised it was because of the rock solid guilt i'd been living with at having put up with (and, by association, sanctioning) next level amounts of minor harassment and talking about women as though they're there for the taking.

so, this year, i changed my behaviour and my attitude to casual misogyny. and this year i stopped tolerating that behaviour in others. it's lost me some people. it's gained me integrity.

4. douse your face in acid (the good kind). i've tried all sorts of new skincare this year. it turns out my skin likes being gobbled up from the outside in the form of fruit acids. aesthetics aside, there's something incredibly soothing about taking the time out twice a day to look at yourself close up in the mirror and layer witchcraft products on your skin that accomplish no more than serve you to look your best. you are worth the effort and the time.

5. i got a promotion. i left the place i'd worked for over a decade and i started somewhere where i knew nobody, or anything about the subject area. it was bloody terrifying and bloody exhilarating to have to rely on my wits. it aged me ten years (good thing i'd discovered hyaluronic acid, eh) but oh did it make me  realise i can push myself off a cliff and land on my feet.

text:
the year of #women

2018 marked another historic uprising of female voices, another high-point of the women's revolution that is taking place across the world. #2018 was the year of women. 
2018 was remarkable year for our movement as we celebrated the 10th anniversary of #femen. the first decade of our history ends with pride for numerous fights against male domination, with sisterhood among the activists in 4 corners of the planet and with dreams and aspirations for the future. from ukraine to france and to the rest of the world. from kiev students, to women of different age and backgrounds in france, germany, spain, sweden, netherlands, belgium, mexico, brazil, turkey, the usa, venezuela and czech republic. that's the journey femen made so far and we are now ready to expand further. 
in 2018, femen continued to give a sextremist lesson to the patriarchs in power like turkish president recep erdogan and the us president donald trump. driving across the champs-elysees in paris, trump's motorcade was stoped twice by our angry political bodies. that's our female revenge. that's how we grab back patriarchy by the balls! 
in 2018 femen also contributed to the worldwide female uprising #metoo. our activists chased the celebrity perpetrators and made sure they learn that female bodies aren't always sexual objects at their disposal. we made them hear angry loud female voices. following our actions against woody allen and roman polanski, in 2018 we've faced again silvio berlusconi and finally caught bill cosby as he was about to be sentenced for numerous crimes. 
2018 was the year of women with numerous victories for women in different countries. yet, the fight isn't over. it is only the beginning of the next step in our revolution. femen prepares itself for the next year of female fight and femen is ready for the second decade of our topless revolt. with new branches in venezuela and czech republic, with new ideas and strategies, with the same anger and courage, our female soldiers are ready to continue the peaceful fight for equality and dignity of everyone. 
let 2019 be the year of equality, justice and peace. let's make 2019 the year of women again! #feminism

text:
the year of women
2018 marked another historic uprising of female voices, another high-point of the women's revolution that is taking place across the world. #2018 was the year of #women. 
2018 was remarkable year for our movement as we celebrated the 10th anniversary of #femen. the first decade of our history ends with pride for numerous fights against male domination, with sisterhood among the activists in 4 corners of the planet and with dreams and aspirations for the future. from #ukraine to #france and to the rest of the world. from kiev students, to women of different age and backgrounds in france, germany, spain, sweden, netherlands, belgium, mexico, brazil, turkey, the usa, venezuela and czech republic. that's the journey femen made so far and we are now ready to expand further. 
in 2018, femen continued to give a sextremist lesson to the patriarchs in power like turkish president recep #erdogan and the us president donald #trump. driving across the champs-elysees in paris, trump's motorcade was stoped twice by our angry political bodies. that's our female revenge. that's how we grab back #patriarchy by the balls! 
in 2018 femen also contributed to the worldwide female uprising #metoo. our activists chased the celebrity perpetrators and made sure they learn that female bodies aren't always sexual objects at their disposal. we made them hear angry loud female voices. following our actions against woody allen and roman polanski, in 2018 we've faced again silvio berlusconi and finally caught bill cosby as he was about to be sentenced for numerous crimes. 
in 2018 we've denounced #homophobia of conservative groups who deny the rights of gay couples for medically assisted procreation in france as well as the hate crimes against #lgbt+ community in putin's russia, in tunisia and egypt. we've defended our abortion rights with protests in germany and spain and raised up against xenophobia and sexism of the far right groups across europe. 
in 2018 we stood with heroes of freedom of speech and consciences like asia bibi in pakistan and oleg sentsov in russia. femen also supported the imprisoned in france artist pyotr p

the year of women

2018 marked another historic uprising of female voices, another high-point of the women's revolution that is taking place across the world. #2018 was the year of #women. 
2018 was remarkable year for our movement as we celebrated the 10th anniversary of #femen. the first decade of our history ends with pride for numerous fights against male domination, with sisterhood among the activists in 4 corners of the planet and with dreams and aspirations for the future. from #ukraine to #france and to the rest of the world. from kiev students, to women of different age and backgrounds in france, germany, spain, sweden, netherlands, belgium, mexico, brazil, turkey, the usa, venezuela and czech republic. that's the journey femen made so far and we are now ready to expand further. 
in 2018, femen continued to give a sextremist lesson to the patriarchs in power like turkish president recep #erdogan and the us president donald #trump. driving across the champs-elysees in paris, trump's motorcade was stoped twice by our angry political bodies. that's our female revenge. that's how we grab back #patriarchy by the balls! 
in 2018 femen also contributed to the worldwide female uprising #metoo. our activists chased the celebrity perpetrators and made sure they learn that female bodies aren't always sexual objects at their disposal. we made them hear angry loud female voices. following our actions against woody allen and roman polanski, in 2018 we've faced again silvio berlusconi and finally caught bill cosby as he was about to be sentenced for numerous crimes. 
in 2018 we've denounced #homophobia of conservative groups who deny the rights of gay couples for medically assisted procreation in france as well as the hate crimes against #lgbt+ community in putin's russia, in tunisia and egypt. we've defended our abortion rights with protests in germany and spain and raised up against xenophobia and sexism of the far right groups across europe. 
in 2018 we stood with heroes of freedom of speech and consciences like asia bibi in pakistan and oleg sentsov in russia. femen also supported the imprisoned in france artist pyotr pavl

text:
the students of howard university film and television program call for the establishment of a department of cinematic arts and television, effective fall 2019. howard has the most comprehensive film program, and offers the only mfa in film, of any hbcu in the united states. howard university has the only minority owned pbs affiliate in the nation. for decades since the founding of the film program in 1971, we have been fulfilling a national and global need for women storytellers and storytellers of color. still, there is no hbcu in the united states with a department dedicated to the study of cinematic arts and television - we can change this.

we are calling for the first department of cinematic arts and television, at any hbcu in the nation, to include the following components:

a) independently administered budget. 
b) independently managed equipment center and facilities. 
c) shared governance by the students and faculty over said budget, equipment center, curriculum development and implementation of the undergraduate and graduate bfa and mfa programs, as well as program and instructor evaluation. 
d) and a commitment to attract more of the most qualified professors in the industry, and to continue to produce graduates of the finest caliber.

support us by signing the petition, share the campaign with everyone you know, and let howard university president wayne a. i. frederick know that the time is now for a howard university department of cinematic arts and television.

since 1971, the howard university film program has produced and/or supported the most highly trained and widely acclaimed storytellers, including: bradford young, hans charles, ernest dickerson, arthur jafa, jenn nkiru, malik sayeed, alan ferguson, sehkar kammula, faraday okoro, lodi matsetela, lekgetho makola, nijla mumin, maori karmael holmes, floyd rance, yao ramesar, and shirikiana aina.

with the likes of stanley nelson, michelle parkerson, julie dash, and haile gerima having served as faculty in the program.

in the new era of #oscarssowhite, #timesup, and #metoo the film and television industry is clearing space to #tellblackstories.

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: â€œwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.â€ documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takersâ€™ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebookâ€™s â€œplatform policyâ€ allowed only collection of friendsâ€™ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebookâ€™s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate â€œinformation warfareâ€ against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
short-term memory loss is one of the many complications of ptsd (post-traumatic stress disorder.) your brains chemicals have been altered as your mind begins to unpack the trauma that has happened. 
my memory had deteriorated after i had completely cut contact. my mind began to upload a file that seems to be beyond capacity. the small files - day to day ones, tend to crash or are forgotten very quickly. ğŸ¤¦ğŸ½â€â™€ï¸ once i had made up my mind that enough was enough. i cut all contact. i didnâ€™t say goodbye. i called out the bs and watched him scramble up excuses after excuses. i knew i was going to be the one that stopped him in his tracks.

i see a woman that is rising from the ashes. i give myself time out and patience. i absolutely love the skin i am in, the marks on my body that were left from him are now my battle wounds, each day they fade, each day i grow a little more, discover something entirely new about myself. the best part of this journey. rediscovering what i thought would never be discovered again. ğŸ’šğŸŒ¿ğŸ’š .  #offmychest #hearmetoo #metoo #wecandobetter #arttherapy #creative #creativeseries #rediscoveringmyself

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: â€œwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.â€ documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takersâ€™ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebookâ€™s â€œplatform policyâ€ allowed only collection of friendsâ€™ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebookâ€™s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate â€œinformation warfareâ€ against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
trigger warnings: disordered eating, mental health, assualt. .
i don't own a lot of photos of myself. occasionally, my mother shares a few with me and it leaves a knot in my stomach. diet culture has sold us the lie that if we can achieve a target weight, we will be respected, successful, and happy. diet culture teaches us to conflate size with health, achievement, and well-being. .
at 23, i had reached my target bmi. at 23, i could not get out of bed in the morning without a beer. i could not get through my lunch without the fistful of cigarettes i substituted for food. i thought if i ran enough, lifted enough, fasted enough; no one would know how utterly wrecked my body and soul were from a violent sexual assualt. friends, family, therapists told me how well adjusted i was based on (my size*) my rigorous commitment to a misinterpretation of health. .
for half of my life i set a weight loss goal for myself at this time every year - and i often met those goals. i wasn't healthy. i was not happy. .
in the past 6 years, i gained weight. i also fell in love with myself for reasons that had nothing to do with my size. i had a number of achievements - i obtained my masters as a first generation student,  prioritized my mental health, redefined wellness and nutrition for myself (based on the health at every size model), and opened myself up to traveling to new countries to learn new ways of being. i set new, more challenging goals and it was every bit more fulfilling when i met them. i chose to grow. .
the reason i am sharing this is because a fat person has to deal with a constant stream of well-intentioned assholes who feel compelled to make assumptions and suggestions about your health - about your choices - and i am telling you you can resist that. you get to define health for yourself. full stop. .
and for those who judge on the basis of size - i  really hope you take this year to reflect on your own conditioning, your fear, and your own mental wellness. hate is not a good look. . 
wishing you all the very best in 2019. 
#bodypositive #bopowarriors #happynewyear #healthateverysize #newyearsameme #radicalselflove #lovebig #metoo #reflecting #healing #thriving

text:
what an amazing year! i have been blessed to meet so many wonderful new friends and god opened the door to great opportunities to share my story, "call me master- a memoir surviving abuse". i stepped out of my comfort zone to share, educate and inspire others. to be a voice to those victims that are no longer with us. thank you for the support and love! 
if you are trapped in an abusive relationship call your lical shelter or call the police. if you know someone in an abusive relationship please don't give up on them. listen, be patient with them, and remind them they are not to blame. find resources from your local shelter or the police to help. stay safe! big hugs!

text:
i got my very first copy of @gtwomanmagazine today and so much excitement and gratitude is swirling around in my heart. all i can say is i am humbled by the opportunity to share my story â€” beauty from the ashes: my journey of transformation. my arms are wide open and my story is enormously transparent. i have swung from giddy highs to anxious lows during the process of opening up and writing more of my story for all to hear. but itâ€™s mine. and as i say in my article, â€œmy heart is full of joy, my life is filled with hope and my kids are thriving. i stand on my sacred ground and claim love above all else and i trust that love will be greater than any obstacle that comes my way.â€ thank you, my friends, for being my village, my rock to stand on, my shoulder to cry on, my feet to dance with and my sunshine on cloudy days. i have the best friends a girl could ask for and an iron clad community with hearts of gold. yes. this is my story, these are my people and this is my very best life chapter yet. #thisisme â¤ï¸
.

text:
ğŸ‘¹â›ª happy nyeee hail satan. an excerpt from ali kellogg's article on a destruction ritual experience - "then one year, we started bringing physical objects to destroy. things that bore some kind of sentimental value we hung onto, but in reality just sat in a box in a closet somewhere and caused us negative emotions when we remembered they were there. we felt by hanging onto these objects, we were holding onto the hope of a failed relationship or the improvement of someoneâ€™s character, or a good memory we would cling to like this object was a life raft, but all it did was hurt us. we took turns smashing our objects with hammers, knives, and throwing the pieces into the fire. afterwards, i felt a sense of empowerment i had never felt before, and an epiphany. the relationship was done, but i had let it still continue to hurt me by giving power to this stupid little plastic tambourine and a box of paper. by hanging onto them, i allowed the toxicity to seep into my everyday and gave something inanimate delusional purpose.
the destruction ritual serves this very purposeâ€Šâ€”â€Šdestroying objects that we have given the power to hurt us. itâ€™s a form of self love, as you are trusting that by destroying these stupid things, you will be stronger and lighter, so to speak, after doing it. so much of our culture revolves around material possessions. our social status is assigned by what we have, our self worth is measured by what we have. we go into debt to buy cars and clothes and technology that pollutes the environment and will probably break and need to be replaced within two years anyway. in a way, you could stretch it and say the destruction ritual is your own petty way of combating the detrimental effects of capitalism."
.
.
.
.
.

text:
#actressroundtable2018 by #rajeevmasand confused me. earlier the #actorsroundtable2018 i had thoroughly enjoyed, with the soulful wisdom of #pankajtripathi tripathy, the way he wove his words, the light hearted banter and idiosyncrasies of #ranveersingh, the introspection by #vickykaushal, the passionate discourse on the craft of acting by #rajkummarrao and of course as ranveer put it, the man behind all of 2018â€™s #roi, #ayushmankhurrana with his usual easy going unassuming humility. they discussed on method, movies, #metoo and many more...
with the #actress i first of all found the #questions #frivolous... i donâ€™t recall the men being asked â€œwho was their crushâ€.... there wasnâ€™t a single question on their craft... the whole panel were interrupting each other white #tabu seemingly sleepwalking...(well, we know how deftly she had pulled out a #ladymacbeth), #deepika was graceful... however two most embarrassing and disappointing part of the round table was one #ranimukherjee take on #metoo... she said in very many words, â€œ women should learn to avoid and also learn martial arts!!â€ ridiculous!! others politely tried to bring her to see the perspective, but to no avail!! the other was the question on #patriotism vs #jingoism...i totally lost what #aliabhatt wanted to say... she started with her belief in the #futulity of war to finally realising, (yes hold your breath)..â€jawans at the border guarding your countryâ€ and then #anoushka  joining in to speak of her #faujidad... even questions which were meant to push the panelist towards introspecting in their process and craft turned out to be a dampner...tabu when asked in playing #simmi inn#andhadhun, a woman with no conscience, was interrupted by our #aliamiss, since she didnâ€™t want spoilers...before she could watch the film..ğŸ™„
for me it was uncomfortable watching this... since the round table which started with the premise of celebrating #bollywood having #authorbacked roles for #women turned out to be a frivolous chat show which could have been moderated better and the questions could have been picked keeping in mind the varying range!!

we are honored to be the recipient of an immensely generous gift from @onpointcu!
.
knowing that their wonderful employees nominated and selected @raphaelhousepdx as a beneficiary makes this all the more meaningful, and we loved having members of their team visit our space.
.
this incredible contribution will fund nearly 8 months of safe days and nights for individual survivors in our emergency shelter. that is life-saving, and will help countless families end the cycle of violence and rebuild their lives after abuse. we truly couldn't be more grateful!

text: #latergram one of my proudest moments, as a sexual assault survivor and #socialworker in the making. what touched me most about this was when a young man came up to me after, in tears. he said his mother had broke down as a result of the kavanaugh hearing and told him she had been raped 50 years ago. he said he felt so lost, hopeless, and hurt. we hugged tightly and i told him to just love on her and let her know people are fighting the injustice. he thanked me for speaking out because he said it felt like i was speaking on behalf of his mother. our stories are different, but the human element is the same. fight against injustice. fight for humanity. #ncsss #futuresocialworker #believevictims #metoo

text:
today i did something i never thought i would have the courage to do. today marks 2 years since my parents received the most horrific call of their life. the call that would shake any parent when you answer at 2am in the morning hearing your daughter screaming & choking on her own tears.

today was the day that changed my entire life. today is the date i was sexually assaulted. 
today is the day i am sharing my journey of what it took to heal & becoming #becomingramirez.

i drove to the gas station â›½ï¸ that i stumbled into after i was assaulted and asked to speak with the indian man who helped me through the door.
cleaned up my wounds.
covered me with anything he could place over my half dressed body.
grabbed napkins to dry the blood and gave me water.

i never revisited the gas station nor the scene of it all because it was too traumatizing but today i did ğŸ™ğŸ½ âœ¨i wanted to thank him because he was the one to call 911 & he saved my life! âœ¨
_
_
_
to the indian man who rescued me that night when all i wanted to do was run home to my parents & keep all of this a secret.... thank you for calling ğŸ˜­âœ¨ because of you
i was healing right then and there with your counsel & your compassion!

the simple act of him making that call 
allowed me to get a year of therapy, support group & justice from the cityâ€™s police department... all because of his call & description of me!
-
-
-
although i could not locate you sir, 2 years later on this very day. thank you so much!
-
-
-
full day of my healing is in my instastories if you wish to see what i was able to do. the wee bit of courage i had in me before i completely broke down crying to my girlfriend @isabelsth  in front of the gas station.

this is healing from sexual trauma! 
this is #becomingramirez .
.
.
.
.

maude girard is a french photographer born in annecy. with a journalistic background she is currently developing several long-term projects on a documentary basis. inspired by a lineage of strong women and by the movement #metoo and its corollaries, she is exploring the concept of femininity. through her first documentary project, pont-marie ou lâ€™appÃ©tit du rÃªve (pont-marie or the appetite for the dream), she witnesses marieâ€™s search and process of identity building as a musician and a millennial woman. wondering about social norms and self-definition obstacles, maude is also questioning her own feminine history through another project called legacy as both a photographer and a granddaughter. she will be presenting her recent ongoing photographic bodies of work evoking her evolving approach and the impact of #metoo on those projects.

text: iâ€™m leaving the person i was behind. not the person i was before i met you but the person you made me. i was weak, broken, paranoid and terrified. i slept in gym shoes for the first couple months. sleep has never been the same. every time i closed my eyes i saw you. and when i would distract myself for a moment you would force yourself back in my mind. eventually lack of sleep would turn into oversleep. and distractions turned into drugs and alcohol to force out your image.  anything to escape. the thing is that this wasnâ€™t the first time that itâ€™s happened. i was 7years old the first time. 7years old. what you did just brought everything i tried to push away come right back to the surface. but not anymore. iâ€™ve been a prisoner of yours for a long time. canâ€™t smell certain smells, go to certain areas, do anything that reminds me. this painting i made here is me leaving her behind. i didnâ€™t use red paint. i used my blood. i cut my self to feel the pain and as it drips down my finger the pain leaves me too. i used blood because this is the last time iâ€™ll shed blood from you. the last time i will feel pain from you. the last time i will be broken by you. from this point on my pain will be turned to art. i will pour everything into creating. you took so much from me. and now iâ€™m taking it back. this painting is literally a part of me. it was very therapeutic but also took so so much out of me emotionally. i hope you enjoy and please please please share. share because itâ€™s important. share becoi hope to inspire others to turn this pain of sexual assault into something they canâ€™t take away from you. make something beautiful. theyâ€™ve taken so much from us. take it right back. we are powerful! we are beautiful and we have been silent for long enough! #metoo #painting #blood #share #metoomovement

â€¢

text: this could be set anywhere because of the absence of names, but it feels so furiously today that it was a slight shock to realise, some way into the pages, that it's modeled after #belfast during the #troubles. the troubles are not central to the story, but the effect political and social divisions have on everyday life is: the hypervigilance of people, the codes of behaviour alien to anyone not in the division, the dogma that resistence itself falls into, the power of rumor and association with those 'beyond the pale'. all brought home through the unwanted attention a powerful man bestows on the 18 year old protagonist and her strategies in responding to him, her maybe-boyfriend, her family and community. i loved it, devoured it, enjoyed the unorthodox style from writing. imagine a long fireside tale, told in stream of consciousness, ebbing and flowing every now and then around ascerbicly funny sentences. #epicwin #milkman #annaburns #bookstagram

text:
who should pay on the first date? 
i asked this question to a focus group of men, women and teenagers ranging from 16-42. what was fascinating is that, even though there is no hint of gender in the question, the answers are mostly gender based.

it seems silly given if the same gender is dating then who pays? 
the question should be answered from a social perspective e.g. the person doing the inviting and not a gender based one.

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
surround yourself with healthy resources and establish healthy boundaries. healthy resources could be a loving relationship, nutritious foods, nurturing touch, connections with nature, or a satisfying hobby. a healthy emotional boundary does not accept words or energy directed your way that are not appropriate or healing. *credit: suzanne scurlock-durana from full body presence). hereâ€™s one of my healthy resources: my grandma barbara. â¤ï¸â¤ï¸
.
the holidays bring us closer to family and inevitably that allows us to have deeper conversations beyond the â€œlikesâ€ and â€œheartsâ€ of social media. i had a long conversation with my step mom who works with women and children who have fallen victim to or are at risk of domestic violence. maybe itâ€™s just me and my desire to have real conversations with people, instead of superficial small talk about the weather and social activities, that brings me to these deeper conversations.
.
if youâ€™re in a relationship thatâ€™s not filling you up, not allowing you to be yourself or you donâ€™t feel safe, get out. no, itâ€™s not easy. yes, you will be scared and go through a period of extreme grief over the loss. yes, help is available. yes, you can do it. you deserve better, regardless of what youâ€™ve been told or what you secretly believe about yourself. you deserve to be treated with respect and honor and love. .
no one, whether itâ€™s a parent, a boyfriend, a girlfriend, a spouse or a friend, have the right to harm you through their words, touch, controlling manipulative behavior, or finances. .
once youâ€™re in a safe place, seek out the healing help you need. you may not have considered physical therapy to be a place to receive the kind of help you need to recover. however, the kind of physical therapy i do is exactly what you need. you wonâ€™t be put on a stationary bike or do needless, mindless exercise here. at the healing spot youâ€™ll find the gentle healing touch your body needs to release the pain within. the pain of sexual abuse, verbal abuse, physical abuse, criticism, fear, grief, anxiety. i will hold the healing space you need and iâ€™m just a phone call away 719-270-1123. #womenshealthphysicaltherapy

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
reviewing 2018 and shamelessly tooting my own horn:

1. the 505 boys - as the great @scottjmulligan said "it was the best of times and the worst of times" #lajavanaise
2. turning 21 surrounded by my ucla crew
3. valedictorian of @sciencespo, got my law degree from @univlorraine, ended up on the dean's honors list at @ucla, and reached the 96th percentile on my #lsat
4. in october, the book i've assisted prof. laure murat in writing on the aftermath of #metoo was published in france
5 & 6. i am lucky to have amazing friends around me helping me going through hard times - @lilirochettemonnoury @emma__vinct @senala9 i don't deserve y'all
7. i had the great opportunity to be an intern at the williams institute @uclalawschool. check out their amazing work on lgbt people and rights in the us and all around the world
8. enjoying my last month in la with the best people
9. resting and spending time with family
10. a last goodbye to los angeles and my wonderful #bruins experience
name: Alex Schulz

text:
according to a study by ibm and two organizations based out of delhi and their study of wikipedia entries on 4,000 bollywood movies between 1970 and 2017 by ibm and two delhi-based organizations showed that male characters were mentioned nearly twice as many times as their female counterparts. 
sexism was prevalent as female characters are mostly described as â€œbeautifulâ€ and â€œattractiveâ€ whereas men are called â€œstrongâ€ and â€œsuccessfulâ€. while women go on to marry or love, men were likely to kill or shoot. 
stereotypes or sexist ideas and constructs prevail in the bollywood industry, the item-numbers that shows scantily clad women surrounded by drunk men drooling over her â€œspicyâ€ or â€œtheekaâ€ body to an upbeat, irrelevant song. 
when the #metoo movement arrived in the industry, it provided many in the industry and the country in whole hope, hope that justice would be served, hope that this massive evil would be erased. but the movement almost like a soda can fizz at first but then almost instantly died out. 
what happened to the movement? why has no action taken place? why did the buck stop at bollywood?
another interesting thought to ponder upon is why did the media houses stop reporting the incidents? did people lose interest? or was the â€œmasalaâ€ or the drama just too boring for the public? 
some people believe the movement died down due to the false accusations people were making. to all these people we just have one question to say? have you got to be out of your f*****g mind? 
what next? do we just wait, or are we finally going to speak up about it? something needs to happen, and it needs to happen soon.

stereotypes or sexist ideas and constructs prevail in the bollywood industry, the item-numbers that shows scan notily clad women surrounded by drunk men drooling over her â€œspicyâ€ or â€œtheekaâ€ body to an upbeat, irrelevant song. 
when the #metoo movement arrived in the industry, it provided many in the industry and the country in whole hope, hope that justice would be served, hope that this massive evil would be erased. but the movement almost like a soda can fizz at first but then almost instantly died out. 
what happened to the movement? why has no action taken place? why did the buck stop at bollywood?
another interesting thought to ponder upon is why did the media houses stop reporting the incidents? did people lose interest? or was the â€œmasalaâ€ or the drama just too boring for the public?

what next? do we just wait, or are we finally going to speak up about it? something needs to happen, and it needs to happen soon.

the glitz and the glamour is not the only thing bollywood consists of. 9 out of 10 times, behind every movie, there is a horrifying story of the casting couch. this is even worse for newcomers, people who are trying to find their big break in the industry, men, women anyone who wants to make it big, almost always has to go through this horrendous path. sakshi shivanand captures this casting couch phenomenon in its whole essence by saying â€œits a professional hazard, you gotta go with itâ€. within bollywood, it has now become a norm, a quid pro quo situation. people in power exploit the weakers ones, the ones trying to achieve something. they think itâ€™s their right to receive sexual favours from aspiring stars for them to cast them in their movies. big names such as ranveer singh too, have come up and told how even men in the industry are not immune to this. the casting couch culture actually existed in bollywood, a news channel conducted a sting operation. it is visibly clear as shakti kapoor (on whom the operation was conducted) asks for sex in return to a young aspiring actress in order to help her with her career. this clip shows the monstrous world of bollywood which is generally hidden under false fantasies of stardom. the worst part about the casting couch culture is that when smaller, unrecognized players make noise about it, they are either subdued or are crushed. this can be seen in the videos throughout. this is one of the major reasons why people do not want to speak about it, in totality, it is a career suicide. this too can be observed by the actress who spoke out, launched an fir and now is not getting any roles. in a culture which constantly makes people choose certain paths to achieve success, which focuses more on peopleâ€™s assets rather than their acting skills, it is necessary for big players to come out and speak up about more harsher realities. this is the very reason why actresses such as kalki koechlin have now come out, open in the public and started making people aware of how grave this issue is and how this is the real bollywood under the veil which the public needs to help change.

text:
artifact 4 - tanushreeâ€™s duttaâ€™s metoo case
miss tanushree dutta, who had once held the title miss india and has appeared in multiple bollywood can surely be termed an active part of bollywood. however, bollywood owes her another debt. miss dutta helped trigger bollywoodâ€™s own metoo movement which gave many women to come to come ahead and speak on harassment that is often concealed in the industry.in september 2018, dutta accused a veteran bollywood actor, nana patekar of trying to sexually harass her during the shoot of a song. she further claimed that she was harassed by goons on refusal. though, nana patekar firmly denied any wrongdoing, te incident gained much popularity. what, however, was found shocking was peopleâ€™s reaction on the incident. while many did support dutta, many called her names and abused her quite vocally for being an â€˜attention seekerâ€™. many called it a publicity stunt and how she was â€˜asking for itâ€™, because she had given indecent scenes in her movies. there was also a lot of slutshaming and bodyshaming all over the internet after the incident.it just went to show how indian populace would not back out of abusing someone, to defend their â€˜starsâ€™, while some just do not understand the meaning of consent, which is worrying. some people did, however extend their full support to dutta and appealed to people to believe the survivors, this batch also included many popular celebrities. the rest, however, begged off commenting and kept finding excuses to be diplomatic, in typical bollywood fashion.
whatever the verdict be, it cannot be denied that tanushree dutta did bring an issue that was long in waiting into the front. harassment in bollywood has so long suppressed, if the statistics that came forth were anything to believe. this movement gave courage to many- actors and non-actors alike to come and speak on this taboo subject. it also gave a hope to the other fields of india that face harassment to come forth, because everything else that happens in india, bollywood, hopefully, set an example on the youth to come forward if they suffer as such. 
and tanushree dutta is undeniably to be credited for the same.
